04773nam a22008055i 9783110799132DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232024gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831107991327 a10.1515/97831107991322doi  a(DE-B1597)627030  a(OCoLC)1411307756  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLIT0000002bisacsh1 aKünzler, Sarah, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMemory and Remembering in Early Irish Literature :bBeyond the Backward Look /cSarah Künzler. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2023] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (X, 288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMemory and the Medieval North ,x2699-7339 ;v200tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tContents -- t1 Introduction -- t2 Ancestral Topographies? Memory, Places, and Landscape(s) -- t3 Long Live the Eyewitness: Gaining Access to the Past in Early Irish Literature -- t4 Memory’s Dark Twin? Forgetting and its Cultural Impact -- t5 Toward a Conclusion: Past, Present and Future Revisited -- tAppendix -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIreland possesses an early and exceptionally rich medieval vernacular tradition in which memory plays a key role. What attitudes to remembering and forgetting are expressed in secular early Irish texts? How do the texts conceptualise the past and what does this conceptualisation tell us about the present and future? Who mediates and validates different versions of the past and how is future remembrance guaranteed? This study approaches such questions through close readings of individual texts. It centres on three major aspects of medieval Irish memory culture: places and landscapes, the provision of information about the past by miraculously old eye-witnesses, and the personal, social and cultural impact of forgetting. The discussions shed light on the relationship between memory and forgetting and explore the connections between the past, present and future. This shows the fascinating spatio-temporal identity constructions in medieval Ireland and links the Irish texts to the broader European world. The monograph makes this rich literary sources available to an interdisciplinary audience and is of interest to both a general medievalist audience and those working in Cultural Memory Studies.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aCultural studies. 4aEnglisch+Litertaur+Irland. 4aIrland. 4aMemory studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aIreland.  aIrish literature.  acultural studies.  amemory studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2024 Part 1z978311133219208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary Studies 2023 Englishz978311131918608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary Studies 2023z9783111318264oZDB-23-DSP0 cEPUBz97831107992240 cprintz978311079909540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311079913240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110799132423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110799132/original  a978-3-11-131918-6  EBOOK PACKAGE Literary Studies 2023 Englishb2023  a978-3-11-131929-2  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishb2023  a978-3-11-133219-2  DG Plus DeG Package 2024 Part 1b2024  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2023  aZDB-23-DSPb2023